history.content:
189 is always a very high workload class regardless of who is teaching it (though you’re right that the Sahai iteration is notoriously hard in particular). On the other hand, 188 is definitely on the easier side of upper divs (definitely still hard though, some people underestimate it).

I took these two classes together (189 with Shewchuk, 188 with a different prof—though I think 188 is somewhat more standardized in terms of difficulty), and probably spent about 4-5x more time on 189 than 188. 189 was quite a bit more useful though. 188 is more of a survey class into various methods in AI; that’s definitely useful, but it doesn’t get very deep into the theory/math of ML like 189 does.

children.subject: 189 is definitely much more difficult than 188 in terms of workload, although the 188 exams can be a doozy

history.content:
I'm trying to change up my schedule and I wanted to see what would be the better move. To me right now these classes are the same in terms of I don't need one or the other for research or anything, so I'm just wondering about their difficulty. And by difficulty I mean like workload each week, pacing, concepts covered, and of course if the exams are curveballs haha.

This spring CS 188 is with Professor Dawn Song and CS 189 is with Professor Jonathan Shewchuk, but I'd also appreciate any insight on comparing the classes themselves, doesn't have to be iterations taught by specifically those professors! (though I know Professor Sahai's iteration of CS 189 is historically very difficult)
history.subject: Is CS 188 harder or CS 189 harder?
